<TEXTAREA NAME="ReplyMessage" ROWS=20 COLS=75 WRAP="VIRTUAL">[QUOTE]Originally posted by lar:
[I]Hi all,

Three new screenshots coming up within 20 minutes. 

The first shows some of the light effects you get in the game (How much lights do you think are there in that shot ?)

The second illustrates somewhat how story gets told in "Project C". If somebody says the orcs are up to something, it usually means that somewhere in the game world something is really happening. The nice thing is that it is up to you what to do with it.  

For instance, in this screenshot, which is just from a test (which had the intention of screwing up my system), I gave a troop of orcs the order to kill Zandalor. Zandalor (the guy with the funny hat from the first screenshot) is in his keep, and the orcs are somewhere in the forest. It takes them some time to reach the castle, and in my test it's up to the player to stop them. Obviously there's far too many of them to kill all at once, especially since they are equipped with evasive behavior.  By the time I kill some of them, they'll have reached Zandalor.  Now I know there is a troop of elven rangers nearby, so if I can get the troop at the entrance of the castle in time, they'll probably be able to stop the orcs. The problem is of course getting them there, and as it is not part of the story (remember it's just a test), that means that I just can't go up to an elf and say ,"Hey dude, follow me".  In my current version the elves are relentless hunters which means they don't give up once they decided to attack something, so what I did was to lure some zombies in the elven camp, the elves started hunting the zombies who, dumb as they are don't switch from enemy, kept on following me, with the result that I was leading a troop of zombies followed by a troop of elves. The orcs, knowing a threat when they see one, engaged the elves and I had a nice war going on.  (Which indeed choked my system as I figured it would, but it didn't crash which was better than I had hoped). The cool thing was that at that moment Zandalor came out of his keep, and having his magic at god level, started freezing and blasting the orcs a gogo. The orcs lost, and I started having visions of what I can do with this game engine  ;) 

The third screenshot is from the ice spell. Some work needs to be done on it, but it gives you and idea. I have to say that once it's converted to jpg, a lot of the subtleties are lost. It looks much better on the game screen, especially the light effects.

All in all, the shots don't look that bad, but please be aware that it is work in progress, and things are going to change. (The keep for instance gets different furniture)


Lar[/I][/QUOTE]

</TEXTAREA>
</td></tr>
